<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920116-0025</DOCNO><DOCID>920116-0025.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- American Electric Power Co.:   Firm's Unit Gets Approval   To Continue Development</HL><DATE>01/16/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4</SO><CO>   AEP</CO><MS>UTILITIES (UTI)</MS><IN>ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)CENTRAL U.S. ELECTRIC UTILITIES (UEC)</IN><GV>ENERGY DEPARTMENT (ERG)</GV><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)OHIO (OH)UNITED STATES (US)WEST VIRGINIA (WV)</RE><LP>   American Electric Power Co., Columbus, Ohio, said the U.S.Department of Energy approved an application filed by itsAppalachian Power unit to continue development of a 340,000kilowatt pressurized fluidized bed combustion plant in NewHaven, W.Va.   The approval will allow the company to continue design ofa commercial demonstration facility for clean coal technologythrough at least January 1994.</LP><TEXT>   In pressurized fluidized bed combustion technology, coalis burned with dolomite, a type of limestone. The sulfurdioxide released by coal and captured by dolomite eliminatesthe need for flue gas desulfurization scrubbers and reducesnitrous oxide emissions.   Under other terms of the approval, construction of a PFBCplant would begin by 1999, or as many as three years earlierif there is a greater demand for electricity in AppalachianPower's service area. American Electric Power will alsorequire public utility commission approval to beginconstruction of the proposed plant.</TEXT></DOC>